---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
import CompressImage from '../../components/tools/CompressImage';
---

<ToolLayout
  title="Compress Photo for Government Form Free Online | Filekrush"
  description="Compress photos to meet government form upload limits. Works for passport, Aadhaar, PAN, visa, and exam applications. No upload, runs in your browser."
  canonical="/compress/for-government"
  heading="Compress Photo for Government Form"
  subheading="Reduce photos to meet government portal upload limits — free, private, instant."
>
  <CompressImage client:only="react" defaultTargetKB={100} />

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="prose prose-gray max-w-none">
      <h2>Common government form photo limits</h2>
      <p>Government portals across India and other countries enforce strict photo upload limits. Here are common requirements:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Indian Passport (PSK)</strong> — photo under 300KB, signature under 80KB</li>
        <li><strong>Aadhaar update</strong> — photo under 50KB</li>
        <li><strong>SSC/RRB exam forms</strong> — photo 20-50KB, signature 10-20KB</li>
        <li><strong>UPSC applications</strong> — photo under 300KB</li>
        <li><strong>PAN card application</strong> — photo under 50KB</li>
        <li><strong>Visa applications</strong> — varies by country, typically 100-500KB</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>How it works</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Drop your photo</strong> — supports JPG, PNG, and WebP.</li>
        <li><strong>Set the exact size limit</strong> — pre-set to 100KB, adjust to match your form's requirement.</li>
        <li><strong>Download</strong> — your photo is ready to upload to the government portal.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Is it safe?</h2>
      <p>Yes. Your photo is processed entirely in your browser. No data is sent to any server. This is especially important for identity documents and government submissions.</p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</ToolLayout>
